data.name: Aila Taylor
data.notes: Aila Taylor worked hard to preserve the North Taranaki reefs. As a result the New Plymouth list includes a number of reefs.

data.name: Apirana Mahuika
data.notes: Api Mahuika was a senior kaumātua of Ngāti Porou, and very supportive of the project, patiently reading the long lists of East Coast names. We recorded in Gisborne, saving me a long trip up the coast.

data.name: Arapera Nitenetara
data.notes: Mrs Governor was blind, and I read each name for her to repeat/correct, then edited my own voice out.

data.name: Autiti Wikiriwhi
data.notes: "Beaker Wickliffe" lived next to Wahiao meeting house, in a house that had half collapsed. It was apparently agreed with his family that he and the house might as well live out their time together.

data.name: Charles Solomon
data.notes: Chartes Solomon was the son of Tommy Solomon, the last "full blooded" Moriori of the Chatham Islands. I included him more for his historical importance, with the help of his son Māui Solomon, since he did not speak the Moriori language. It has since undergone a revival. He was blind and I read him each name. He lived in Temuka, and he gave me some sense of what it meant to say the Moriori died "of despair".

data.name: Euera Manuera
data.notes: I visited Eruera Manuera one afternoon, and he was nearly asleep. His family told me he was better in the morrning, and so it proved. He died very soon after we recorded the names.

data.name: Hohepa Toia
data.notes: Possibly misidentified as his brother Sam

data.name: Hone Turei
data.notes: Later Sir Hone.

data.name: Jane Manahi
data.notes: Aunt Jane Manahi was another old-school kuia, beautifully spoken in both English and Māori, who would brook no nonsense from any young whippersnapper.

data.name: John Bird
data.notes: We recorded in the meeting house, and some women were weaving at the other end. I asked if they could stop, but Mr Bird said, no, their work is tapu too.

data.name: John Rangihau
data.notes: I had known John Rangihou since 1971 and of course he was best qualified to speak for Ngai Tūhoe. It was only by chance that I recorded Waimana without him. It took months to find us both free. We recorded in Studio 1 of Broadcasting House of blessed memory. You can hear his love of the places in his voice. (This is true of many other speakers as well).

geo.recorded: Studio 1, Broadcasting House, Bowen St, Wellington

data.name: John Tangiora
data.notes: I recorded John Tangiora in a tearing hurry, having driven from Ruatoki via Murupara and a back road to Taupo and Napier, and he and Pauline had an appointment not long after. He was in failing health.

data.name: Kara Puketapu
data.notes: Kara Puketapu was chosen by Te Ati Awa as their speaker, and uses a strong Taranaki accent with silent Hs. I discussed with him whether he should make some concession to the previous occupants of Wellington Harbour, Ngati Ira and Ngai Tara. He said "We'll see how it goes" or words to that effect. He made some effort to aspirate "Hātaitai", but the effect is uncomfortable.

data.name: Lena Manuel
data.notes: Lena Manuel was a stalwart of the Māori Women's Welfare League, and I had met her in that context in Wellington, but in the event we recorded in her home in Wairoa. I always had an uphill job persuading women to speak. My standard line was that women needed to know about placenames in composing waiata. I now wish I had worked harder at it.

data.name: Maarire Goodall
data.notes: Sir Tīpene O'Regan directed me to Maarire Goodall when I began the South Island. He was invaluable, pointing me towards most of the speakers and taking over the production of the third print volume. We were both strong-willed but eventually resolved all problems. In the course of this, he became a dear friend.

geo.recorded: Studio 1, Broadcasting House, Bowen St, Wellington
Studio 1, Broadcasting House, Bowen St, Wellington

data.name: Magda Walscott
data.notes: Magda Walscott was a very senior kuia of her region, but very bright.

data.name: Mahia Whatarau-Tainui
data.notes: with Henry Robinson

data.name: Maika Mason
data.notes: Poutini Ngai Tahu

data.name: Malcolm Hoskins
data.notes: Malcom Hoskins is the youngest speaker.

data.name: Manahi Paewai
data.notes: We recorded in the evening and birdsong adds to the track.

data.name: Matawha Durie
data.notes: Mr Durie knew far more names around the family home and Aorangi marae - names for humps and dips in the land, it seemed.

data.name: Matenga Baker
data.notes: We recorded Mr Baker on a winter day with a crackling fire.

data.name: Mere Toia
data.notes: co-speaker with Hohepa Toia and Sam Toia

data.name: Merimeri Penfold
data.notes: Merimeri was my first tutor of Māori, a great scholar of the language, and a beautiful speaker. She helped update Williams' Dictionary, and translated some of Shakespeare's sonnets into Māori. In 1970 she composed a haka against apartheid. It is my eternal regret that when I asked her to record her Far North names, she brought a male speaker with her, and I let her defer to him, so we only hear her say the names that he missed. I resolved to make a greater effort to include women in the South Island section.

data.name: Mita Mohi
data.notes: Mita Mohi is better known as a teacher of the taiaha.

data.name: Paddy Gilroy
data.notes: with George Te Au

data.name: Pakariki Harrison
data.notes: Paki Harrison is better known as a master-carver.

data.name: Pukerau Rangitutea
data.notes: The first recording, at his home in the evening, was a technical disaster for some reason, and I went back later, in the morning, and our recording on the meeting house porch was much more successful. Like many others, he showed his dedication to this project by agreeing undergo the tedious process of recording the names clearly and without background noise, not once but twice.

geo.recorded: Studio 1, Broadcasting House, Bowen St, Wellington

data.name: Raureti Harris
data.notes: and Bob Harris

data.name: Rex Hiakita
data.notes: When I visited Rex Hiakita, he was hesitant, but a would-be rangatira  from another area (with a very poor outline of a facial moko), said "Give me your machine, I'll record your names." Knowing enough not to say "No" outright, I said "Taihoa" and came back to Mr Hiakita later.

data.name: Ru Kotua
data.notes: Ru Kotua initially baulked at recording the names when I showed him a list written in the double-vowel orthography. He wanted nothing to do with it. The first volume was entirely so written in the first instance, and the double vowels were laboriously converted to macrons by the incredibly patient Radio NZ typing pool. When I showed Mr Kotua the version with macrons, he thought they were the greatest thing since sliced bread and all objection evaporated. The recording, outside in a field near Takapau, went happily with birds chirping in the background.

geo.recorded: his office, Victoria University of Wellington

data.name: Sam Toia
data.notes: Possibly misidentified as his brother Hohepa

data.name: Sonny Waru
data.notes: Recording western Taranaki was a tossup between Sony Waru and Huirangi Waikerpuru.I didn't know when I chose Sonny Waru that he was only affiliated to Taranaki through Pariʰaka. (His first name, Taniwharau, gives away his Waikato origin.) Nonetheless he has lived there so long his accent is fully Taranaki.

data.name: Te Aputa ki Wairua Kauri
data.notes: Mrs Kauri smoked constantly and was short of breath throughout the recording. (She died soon after.) You can hear her pride when she says her ancestor's name, Wi Parata.

data.name: Te Rino Tirikatene
data.notes: Rino Tirikātene was a son of Sir Eruera Tirikātene MP and a brother of Whetū Tirikātene-Sullivan MP. He died while standing for Parliament himself, and his son Rino took the seat. He had no tribal affiliation to the Marton region, but was the best possible person to say the names of the many buildings at Rātana.

data.name: Turi Elkington
data.notes: Finding a speaker for Nelson proved difficult, but I had been introduced to Mr Elkington in Waipukurau when I was recording in that area. He had already been enthusiastic for the project, though of course he declined to speak the names so far from his home, so I had no hesitation in going back to him.

data.name: Waiharakeke Waitere
data.notes: Mrs Wai Waitere was a kuia of the old school, a wonderfully distinguished lady, who spoke both beautiful English and Māori. We recorded in her villa in Pūtiki.

data.name: Wiremu Kere Kere
data.notes: Wiremu Kere Kere was my starting point in finding the network of speakers. We shared an office suite in Radio NZ Special Projects for several years.

data.name: Wiremu Parker
data.notes: Wiremu Parker was a pioneer of Māori broadcasting. He coined the term 'te reo irirangi' for radio. Because he was unable to speak for his home territory for obscure reasons, I asked him to read the title names. I recorded him outside in the Wellington Botanic Gardens just of Salamanca Road.

data.name: North Island
data.description: Recorded in two parts - from October to November 1984, and between 1986 and 1990. Partially funded by a Bill Toft Memorial grant. 18,000 km travelled.

data.name: South Island
data.description: Recorded from November 1992 to April 1993. Funded by the NZ Lottery Board Heritage Fund and the Pacific Conservation and Development Trust. 5,000 km travelled.

data.name: Other
data.description: A mix of overseas place names and some addenda.

data.name: Lower North Island
data.description: Names of the North Island, south of a line running from the mouth of the Rangitaiki river, north of Lake Taupo, to the mouth of the Mokau river.

notes.text: I typed the first part at home on an electric typewriter, and the incredibly patient Radio NZ typing pool put up with my micromanagement for over a year. They put the lists on to 8" IBM floppy discs. In the first instance, I used double vowel orthography (Maaori) as I had learnt from Professor Bruce Biggs at Auckland University. It became clear that - largely under the influence of Professor Tīmoti Kāretu at Waikato University - the macron (Māori) was going to win out, and we searched and replaced all 10 vowels (AA EE II OO UU aa ee ii oo uu) with their macronned equivalents - then searched and de-maronned all the wrongly alteredEnglish words such as schōl and mēting. Creating macrons was a job in itself in those days. Each one involved making a subroutine, or macro, of backspace, half-raise, hyphen, half-lower. Before I went out recording, I asked for printouts of the names, but invariably more would have to be added on the road.
notes.recording: The first volume was entirely recorded on a Uher portable reel-to-reel recorder at 7 1/2 inches/second.. At the outset I insisted on using the only stereo recorder of Radio NZ Special Projects, when it was free. I knew that the sound quality would be substantially better in stereo, even though it was only ever a single voice. I made various short forays to southern parts of the North Island, and two big sweeps over several days into Wʰanganui, Taranaki, Taupo, the Urewera, East Coast and Hawkes Bay.

data.name: Upper North Island
data.description: Names of the North Island, north of a line running from the mouth of the Rangitaiki river, north of Lake Taupo, to the mouth of the Mokau river. Also overseas names and some names missed from part 1.

notes.text: Without a grant for the second part, I could not rely on the Radio NZ typing pool, and created the lists at home, teaching myself how to use spreadsheets, which were relatively new in 1986.
notes.recording: Most of the second volume was recorded on the Uher portable reel-to-reel machine, but at one point north of Auckland it broke down and I hired what had once been a top-of-the-line cassette machine. The sound quality, even though I think it had Dolby noise reduction, was decidedly inferior. I completed the Bay of Plenty before mid-1988 and made several long hauls into the King Country, Waikato-Hauraki, Auckland and Northland in 1989-1990.

data.name: South Island
data.funding: NZ Lottery Board Heritage Fund and Pacific Conservation and Development Trust
data.description: Names of the South Island, Stewart Island and southern islands, and the Chatham Islands.

notes.text: Again I created the lists at home, but this time I transmitted them to Dr Maarire Goodall's computer using a precursor of the Internet, a dailup dating service called the Meetboard. At 300 Baud (bits/second), that took hours, and the issues of encoding and decoding the macrons in ASCII were horrendous.
notes.recording: The third volume was entirely recorded on Digital Audio Tape (DAT), like a tiny VCR. The improvement in sound quality is evident. I visited the South Island three times altogether, travelling as far as Tākaka, Hokitika and Tuatāpere.

data.name: Palmerston North
data.notes: By whakapapa, the best person to say these names would have been a descendent of Chief Te Awe Awe, and a daughter of his was insistant that it should be so, but none of his children spoke the language. (In fact Te Awe Awe had lived a double life, going by an English name and playing in a jazz band.) Eventually she relented, and Matawhā "Pompey" Durie, father of Judge Eddie and Dr Mason Durie, said them, and he was amply qualified to do so.

data.name: Waiōuru/Raetihi
data.notes: Mr Mareikura was very frail when I recorded him, and died soon after. I went to the aftermath of his tangi, and secured the permission of his family to use the recording nonetheless.

data.name: Tūrangi/South Taupō
data.notes: Before I recorded any Taupō names, I consulted Sir Hepi Te Heu Heu, who took me to morning tea in Taumarunui. He very modestly declined to speak, but recommended those who did, each of whom was excellent.

data.name: Marton
data.notes: I have often played this track to illustrate the beauty of the Māori language and its placenames.

data.name: Taumarunui
data.notes: I had very much hoped to record the voice of Titi Tihu for the upper Wʰanganui river. I tracked him down, driving along the centre of the road towards Tawataʰa. Aged in his 90s, he spoke only Māori, and my reo was not up to the task explaining my mission and talking him into speaking. The names were instead spoken by his nephew in something of a hurry, in a room overlooking a busy Taumarunui street (perhaps they aren't usually, but this one was).

data.name: Waverley
data.notes: Ruka Broughton (Sr) was ideally qualified to say the names of this region, which closely corresponds to the rohe of his people Ngā Rauru (Kītahi), "Ngā Rauru of the Single Word". Only in the east was there an issue. Some names close to the Wʰanganui river might have belonged to the people of the river. At Ruka's direction, I went back to the Wʰanganui elders and was told, no, they belong to Ngā Rauru. Ruka said "I knew they did, but I wanted them to say it." - a beautiful example of Māori diplomacy, one of many I experienced in my travels.

data.name: Murupara
data.notes: About 30 seconds into this track, at Kiorenui, a fly goes around the microphones. People listening on headphones often try to swat it away.

data.name: Auckland Isthmus (Ancient)
data.notes: Auckland has a rich vein of historial names that are no longer current, or have been modified over time. Thus it became useful to divide it into "ancient" (to approximately the mid-19th century) and "modern".

data.name: Chatham Islands (Ancient)
data.notes: The "ancient" list is intended to be of Moriori names. They are spoken by Charles Solomon, son of the last "full-blooded" Moriori. He did not, however speak the Moriori language.

data.name: Chatham Islands (Modern)
data.notes: The "modern" list is of current Māori names, dating from 1835.
